revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}} [[File:58g aquascape.jpg|thumb|upright=1.4|alt=Aquarium containing a variety of plants and a piece of driftwood, with white gravel at front and a plant with red leaves at the upper left.|58&nbsp;[[United States customary units#Fluid volume|gallon]] (220&nbsp;[[litre]]) freshwater aquascape]] '''Aquascaping''' is the craft of arranging [[aquatic plant]]s, as well as rocks, stones, cavework, or [[driftwood]], in an aesthetically pleasing manner within an [[aquarium]]&mdash;in effect, [[gardening]] under water. Aquascape designs include a number of distinct styles, including the garden-like Dutch style and the Japanese-inspired nature style.<ref name=Hennig/> Typically, an aquascape [[fishkeeping|houses fish]] as well as plants, although it is possible to create an aquascape with plants only, or with rockwork or other hardscape and no plants.
Although the primary aim of aquascaping is to create an artful underwater [[Landscape architecture|landscape]], the technical aspects of tank maintenance and the growth requirements of aquatic plants are also taken into consideration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fishtanksetups.com/aquascaping-guide-for-beginners/|title=Aquascaping 101 – An Introductory Guide for Beginners|date=2017-06-16|work=FishTankSetups|accessdate=2017-06-21|language=en-US}}</ref> Many factors must be balanced in the [[fishkeeping#Aquarium maintenance|closed system]] of an aquarium tank to ensure the success of an aquascape. These factors include [[Filter (aquarium)|filtration]], maintaining [[carbon dioxide]] at levels sufficient to support [[photosynthesis]] underwater, [[Substrate (aquarium)|substrate and fertilization]], [[Aquarium lighting|lighting]], and [[algae]] control.<ref>{{Citation|last=James|first=Barry|year=1986|title=A Fishkeeper's Guide to Aquarium Plants|location=London|publisher=Tetra Press/Salamander Books|isbn=0-86101-207-0}}</ref>
Aquascape hobbyists trade plants, conduct contests, and share photographs and information via the Internet.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mitchell|first=Sherry|title=The Fish Are Fine, but the Plants Are Fabulous|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/416936781.html?dids=416936781:416936781&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+02%2C+2003&author=Sherry+Mitchell&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=The+Fish+Are+Fine%2C+but+the+Plants+Are+Fabulous&pqatl=google|newspaper=Washington Post|date=2 October 2003|accessdate=27 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Wei|first=Tan Karr|title=The exotic trade of aquascaping|url=http://thestar.com.my/metro/story.asp?file=/2007/7/26/central/18263003&sec=central|newspaper=Malaysia Star|date=26 July 2007|accessdate=27 July 2010}}</ref><ref name="aqua">{{Cite news|last=Netburn|first=Deborah|title=Aquascaping: Aquarium meets terrarium in the Japanese-inspired design practice|url=http://www.latimes.com/features/home/la-hm-aquascapes19-2009sep19,0,6049008.story|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=19 September 2009|accessdate=27 July 2010}}</ref> The United States-based Aquatic Gardeners Association has about 1,200 members.<ref name="aqua"/>
== Designs == {{See also|Garden design|Water garden|Micro landschaft}}
=== Dutch style === [[File:The Enchanted Garden by Shay Fertig.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Aquarium densely packed with clumps of fine-leaved plants, some with green leaves and some with red leaves. A large red fish swims at left.|Dutch style aquascape]] The Dutch aquarium employs a lush arrangement in which [[List of freshwater aquarium plant species|multiple types of plants]] having diverse leaf colors, sizes, and textures are displayed much as terrestrial plants are shown in a [[flower garden]]. This style was developed in the [[Netherlands]] starting in the 1930s, as freshwater aquarium equipment became commercially available.<ref name=Hennig/> It emphasizes plants located on terraces of different heights, and frequently omits rocks and driftwood. Linear rows of plants running left-to-right are referred to as "Dutch streets".<ref name=Dutch>Hudson, Robert Paul (30 May 2008), [http://aquabotanic.blogspot.com/2008/05/by-robert-paul-hudson-this-article.html ''Going Dutch''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090810124000/http://aquabotanic.blogspot.com/2008/05/by-robert-paul-hudson-this-article.html |date=10 August 2009 }}.</ref> Although many plant types are used, one typically sees neatly trimmed groupings of plants with fine, feathery foliage, such as ''[[Limnophila aquatica]]'' and various types of ''[[Hygrophila (plant)|Hygrophila]]'', along with the use of red-leaved ''[[Alternanthera reineckii]]'', ''[[Ammania gracilis]]'', and assorted [[Rotala (plant)|''Rotala'']] for color highlights.<ref name=Dutch/> More than 80% of the aquarium floor is covered with plants, and little or no substrate is left visible.<ref name=Dutch/> Tall growing plants that cover the back glass originally served the purpose of hiding bulky equipment behind the tank.<ref name=Hennig>Hennig, Matt (June 2003), Amano versus Dutch: Two art forms in profile, ''Tropical Fish Hobbyist'', pp. 68&ndash;74.</ref> {{Clear}}
=== Japanese styles === ==== Nature style ==== [[File:Peter Kirwan Mountainscape.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|alt=Aquarium with multiple gray stones. The stones are arranged to be low in front and high in the back, with the stones along the back placed vertically in the shape of mountain peaks. Some of the stones are carpeted with small, low, fine, green plants.|A nature style aquascape, suggesting mountains]] A contrasting approach is the "nature aquarium" or Japanese style, introduced in the 1990s by [[Takashi Amano]].<ref name=Hennig/> Amano's three-volume series, ''Nature Aquarium World,'' sparked a wave of interest in aquarium gardening, and he has been cited as having "set a new standard in aquarium management".<ref>[[Herbert R. Axelrod|Axelrod, Herbert R.]], Warren E. Burgess, Neal Pronek, Glen S. Axelrod and David E. Boruchowitz (1998), ''Aquarium Fishes of the World'', Neptune City, N.J.: T.F.H. Publications, p. 718, {{ISBN|0-7938-0493-0}}.</ref> Amano's compositions drew on [[Japanese garden]]ing techniques that attempt to mimic natural landscapes by the asymmetrical arrangement of masses of relatively few species of plants, and which set rules governing [[Japanese rock garden|carefully selected stones]] or driftwood, usually with a single focal point. The objective is to evoke a terrestrial landscape in miniature, rather than a colorful garden. This style draws particularly from the [[Japanese art#Aesthetic concepts|Japanese aesthetic concepts]] of {{nihongo|''[[Wabi-sabi]]''|侘寂}}, which focuses on [[Mono no aware|transience]] and minimalism as sources of beauty. Plants with small leaves like [[List of freshwater aquarium plant species#Listed alphabetically by scientific name|''Glossostigma elatinoides'']], ''[[Eleocharis acicularis]]'', ''[[Eleocharis parvula]]'', ''[[Echinodorus tenellus]]'', [[List of freshwater aquarium plant species#Listed alphabetically by scientific name|''Hemianthus callitrichoides'']], ''[[Riccia fluitans]]'', [[Süsswassertang|small aquatic ferns]], ''[[Staurogyne]] repens'', and [[Java moss]] (''Versicularia dubyana'' or ''Taxiphyllum barbieri'') are often used to emulate grass or moss. Colors are more limited than in the Dutch style, and the hardscape is not completely covered. Fish, or [[Shrimp#Aquaria|freshwater shrimp]] such as ''[[Caridina multidentata]]'' and [[Cherry shrimp|''Neocaridina heteropoda'']], are usually selected to complement the plants and control algae, but for reasons of minimalism the number of species are often limited.<ref>[http://aquascapinglove.com/basics/nature-aquarium-style/ The Nature Aquarium Style], 8 January 2014.</ref>
====Iwagumi style==== [[File:Aquascaping-minilandschaft-lennart.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Aquarium with gray stones arranged to form a tall pointed structure at the right, and a similar but smaller structure at the left. The stone peaks and the foreground are largely but not entirely covered by a short layer of fine textured green plants.|Iwagumi style aquascape, with the ''Oyaishi'' stone at the right]] The Iwagumi style is a specific subtype of the nature style. The {{nihongo|''Iwagumi''|岩組}} term itself comes from the Japanese "rock formation" and refers to a layout where stones play a leading role.<ref>"Iwagumi and Sanzon Iwagumi Aquariums," [http://www.aquatic-eden.com/2007/02/iwagumi-and-sanzon-iwagumi-aquariums.html Aquatic Eden website], 11 February 2007.</ref> In the ''Iwagumi'' style, each stone has a name and a specific role. Rocks provide the bony structure of the aquascape and the typical geometry employs a design with three main stones, with one larger stone and two other smaller stones, although additional rocks can also be used.<ref>[http://aquascapinglove.com/basics/introduction-iwagumi-layout/ The Iwagumi Layout: An Introduction], 7 January 2014</ref> The {{nihongo|''Oyaishi''|親石}}, or main stone, is placed slightly off-center in the tank, and {{nihongo|''Soeishi''|添石}}, or accompanying stones, are grouped near it, while {{nihongo|''Fukuseki''|副石}}, or secondary stones, are arranged in subordinate positions.<ref>[[Takashi Amano|Amano, Takashi]] (2009), How to improve your Iwagumi layout, ''The Aquatic Gardener'', vol. 22, number 1, pp. 37&ndash;41.</ref> The location of the focal point of the display, determined largely by the asymmetric placement of the ''Oyaishi'', is considered important, and follows ratios that reflect [[Pythagorean tuning]].<ref>"The Golden Rule of Aquascaping," [http://www.aquatic-eden.com/2006/11/golden-rule-of-aquascaping.html Aquatic Eden website], 16 November 2006.</ref> {{clear}}
===Jungle style=== [[File:Jungle style aquascape.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.3|alt=Aquarium densely filled with plants, some of which have rosettes of strap-like leaves, and the leaves are intertwined with one another. Some red and blue fishes of various sizes are swimming around.|Jungle style aquascape]] Some hobbyists also refer to a "jungle" (or "wild jungle") style, separate from either the Dutch or nature styles, and incorporating some of the features of them both. The plants are left to assume a natural, untrimmed look. Jungle style aquascapes usually have little or no visible hardscape material, as well as limited open space. Bold, coarser leaf shapes, such as ''[[Echinodorus bleheri]]'', are used to provide a wild, untamed appearance. Unlike nature syle, the jungle style does not follow clean lines, or employ fine textures. A jungle canopy effect can be obtained using combinations of darker substrates, tall plants growing up to the surface, and floating plants that block light, offering a dappled lighting effect. Other plants used in jungle style aquascapes include ''[[Microsorum pteropus]]'', ''[[Bolbitis heudelotii]]'', ''[[Vallisneria americana]]'', ''[[Crinum]]'' species, ''[[Aponogeton]]'' species, ''[[Echinodorus]]'' species, ''[[Sagittaria subulata]]'', ''[[Hygrophila (plant)|Hygrophila]] pinnatifida'', ''[[Anubias]]'' species, and ''[[Limnobium laevigatum]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukaps.org/documents/A%20Guide%20To%20Aquascaping.pdf|title=Our guide to aquascaping styles|last=Farmer|first=George|publisher=UK Aquatic Plant Society|accessdate=28 September 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100815084807/http://www.ukaps.org/documents/A%20Guide%20To%20Aquascaping.pdf| archivedate= 15 August 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aquaportail.com/definition-5493-aquascaping.html|last=Terver|first=Denis|title=Définition de aquascaping|language=French|year=2009|work=Aquaportail|accessdate=28 September 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090922213952/http://www.aquaportail.com/definition-5493-aquascaping.html| archivedate=22 September 2009<!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> {{clear}}
=== Biotopes === [[File:AquariumArtis.jpg|thumb|alt=Aquarium with large stones of various shapes piled high. Some bare sticks are at right, and blue and yellow fish swim in the water.|This [[Lake Malawi]] biotope with [[cichlid]]s is at the [[Natura Artis Magistra|Artis Aquarium]], Amsterdam. Note the absence of green plants in this [[Rift Valley lakes|rift lake]] habitat.]] The styles above often combine plant and animal species based on the desired visual impact, without regard to geographic origin. [[Biotope#Aquaria|Biotope aquariums]] are designed instead to replicate exactly a particular aquatic habitat at a particular geographic location, and not necessarily to provide a gardenlike display. Plants and fish need not be present at all, but if they are, they must match what would be found in nature in the habitat being represented, as must any gravel and hardscape, and even the chemical composition of the water. By including only those organisms that naturally exist together, biotopes can be used to study ecological interactions in a relatively natural setting.<ref>{{Harvnb|James|1986|pp=37&ndash;45}}.</ref><ref>"Biotope Aquaria," [http://fish.mongabay.com/biotope.htm Mongabay.com], 7 December 2004.</ref> {{Clear}}
=== Paludariums === [[File:OfficeSetup13..jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.3|alt=An aquarium viewed from the front. At the bottom front, dark substrate material is built up high at the left and right sides, and low in the center, and its surface is covered by tiny green plants. Water fills the center of the tank, to about halfway up the total height of the tank. Many and various larger plants grow above the water, and over the back wall of the aquarium.|A paludarium]] A [[paludarium]] is an aquarium that combines water and land inside the same environment. These designs can represent habitats including tropical [[rainforest]]s, [[jungles]], [[Stream bank|riverbanks]], [[bogs]], or even the [[beach]].<ref>[http://www.drsfostersmith.com/pic/article.cfm?c=6016&articleid=1446 Paludariums: Discover Water Garden Terrariums!]</ref> In a paludarium, part of the aquarium is underwater, and part is above water. Substrate is built up so that some "land" regions are raised above the waterline, and the tank is only partially filled with water. This allows plants, such as ''[[Cyperus alternifolius]]'' and ''[[Spathiphyllum wallisii]]'', as well as various ''[[Anubias]]'' and some [[Bromeliaceae|bromeliads]], to grow [[wikt:emersed|emersed]], with their roots underwater but their tops in the air, as well as completely submersed. In some configurations, plants that float on the surface of the water, such as ''[[Eichhornia crassipes]]'' and ''[[Pistia|Pistia stratiotes]]'', can be displayed to full advantage. Unlike other aquarium setups, paludariums are particularly well-suited to keeping [[amphibian]]s.<ref>[http://www.paludariums.net/ Paludariums.net].</ref> {{Clear}}
=== Saltwater reefs === [[File:Reef Aquarium At Home.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Aquarium filled densely with corals in many shapes, and bright colors including pink, purple, blue and green.|Reef aquascape]] {{Main|Reef aquarium}} Dutch and nature style aquascapes are traditionally [[Freshwater aquarium|freshwater systems]]. In contrast, relatively few ornamental plants can be grown in a [[Marine aquarium|saltwater aquarium]]. Saltwater aquascaping typically centers, instead, on mimicking a [[coral reef|reef]]. An arrangement of [[live rock]] forms the main structure of this aquascape, and it is populated by [[coral]]s and other [[marine invertebrates]] as well as [[coralline algae]], which together serve much the same aesthetic role as freshwater plants.<ref>{{Citation|ref=harv|last=Borneman|first=Eric H.|year=2004|title=Aquarium Corals: Selection, Husbandry, and Natural History|location=Neptune City, N.J.|publisher=T.F.H. Publications|pages=323&ndash;341|isbn=1-890087-47-5}}</ref><ref>Michael, Scott W. (November 2006), Aquascaping reef habitats, ''[[Aquarium Fish International|Aquarium Fish Magazine]]'', pp. 66&ndash;73.</ref>
Lighting plays a particularly significant role in the reef aquascape. Many corals, as well as [[Tridacna|tridacnid clams]], contain [[Symbiosis|symbiotic]] [[Fluorescence in the life sciences|fluorescent]] algae-like [[dinoflagellate]]s called [[zooxanthellae]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Borneman|2004|pp=47&ndash;55}}.</ref> By providing intense lighting supplemented in the [[ultraviolet]] wavelengths, reef aquarists not only support the health of these invertebrates, but also elicit particularly bright colors emitted by the fluorescent microorganisms.<ref>{{Harvnb|Borneman|2004|pp=326&ndash;334}}.</ref> {{Clear}}
==Techniques== {{See also|Aquarium lighting}} [[File:1856aquariumfresh.png|thumb|left|alt=A drawing in brown ink on an ocher background. A rectangular glass aquarium tank sits on a wooden stand with carved, curled legs, and contains two fish as well as plants with wavy grass-like leaves.|From the [[Victorian era]], aquarists have planted their tanks, as seen in this 1856 example containing ''[[Vallisneria spiralis]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parlouraquariums.org.uk/Papers/b%20AQUARIUM%20HISTORY/History%20Papers/Parlour%20aquarum.htm |title=The first Parlour Aquariums and the Victorian Aquarium Craze |last=Alexander |first=Bob |date=November 2005 |work=History of parlour aquarium |publisher=parlouraquariums.org |accessdate=24 December 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722221227/http://www.parlouraquariums.org.uk/Papers/b%20AQUARIUM%20HISTORY/History%20Papers/Parlour%20aquarum.htm |archivedate=22 July 2011 }}</ref>]] In addition to design, freshwater aquascaping also requires specific methods to maintain healthy plants underwater. Plants are often trimmed to obtain the desired shape, and they can be positioned by tying them in place inconspicuously with thread.<ref>[[Takashi Amano|Amano, Takashi]] (2008), Nature aquarium techniques to create & maintain an aquascape, ''The Aquatic Gardener'', vol. 21, number 2, pp. 8&ndash;17.</ref><ref>Turon, Lluis Ruscalleda (2009), How to use ''Riccia'' and Java moss in the aquarium, ''The Aquatic Gardener'', vol. 22, number 4, pp. 11&ndash;13.</ref> Most serious aquascapers use aquarium-safe fertilizers, commonly in liquid or tablet form, to help the plants fill out more rapidly.<ref>{{Harvnb|James|1986|p=16}}.</ref> Some aquarium substrates containing [[laterite]] also provide nutrients.<ref>{{Harvnb|James|1986|p=28}}.</ref>
It is also necessary to support photosynthesis, by providing light and carbon dioxide. A variety of lighting systems may be used to produce the full [[visible spectrum|spectrum of light]], usually at 2&ndash;4 [[watt]]s per gallon (0.5&ndash;1 watts per litre).<ref name=light /> Lights are usually controlled by a timer that allows the plants to be acclimated to a set cycle.<ref name=light>{{Harvnb|James|1986|pp=20&ndash;29}}.</ref> Depending on the number of plants and fish, the aquascape may also require carbon dioxide supplementation. This can be accomplished with a simple homemade system, using a soda bottle filled with [[Yeast#Aquarium hobby|yeast]], warm water, and sugar, and connected to an [[airstone]] in the aquarium, or with a pressurized CO<sub>2</sub> tank that injects a set amount of carbon dioxide into the aquarium water.<ref>{{Harvnb|James|1986|p=17}}.</ref><ref>Nyberg, Tarah (2003), [http://www.aquatic-gardeners.org/Nyberg_yeast.ppt Yeast CO<sub>2</sub>] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090718160153/http://www.aquatic-gardeners.org/Nyberg_yeast.ppt |date=18 July 2009 }}, (Retrieved 10 October 2009).</ref>
[[File:Nature style aquascape.png|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Aquarium with dark pieces of twisted wood bending from the sides of the tank, towards the center. Dense green plants are all around. Just to the left of center is a darkly shadowed region.|Aquascape evoking an overgrown cave and decaying trees]]
Algae (including [[cyanobacteria]], as well as true algae) is considered distracting and unwanted in aquascaping, and is controlled in several ways. One is the use of [[algae eater|animals that consume algae]], such as some fish (notably [[cyprinid]]s of the genera [[Siamese algae eater|''Crossocheilus'']] and ''[[Gyrinocheilus]]'', and [[catfish]] of the genera ''[[Ancistrus]]'', ''[[Hypostomus]]'', and ''[[Otocinclus]]''), shrimp, or [[snail]]s, to clean the algae that collects on the leaves. A second is using adequate light and CO<sub>2</sub> to promote rapid growth of desired plants, while controlling nutrient levels, to ensure that the plants utilize all fertilizer without leaving nutrients to support algae.<ref>{{Harvnb|James|1986|pp=46&ndash;47}}.</ref>
Although serious aquascapers often use a considerable amount of equipment to provide lighting, filtration, and CO<sub>2</sub> supplementation to the tank, some hobbyists choose instead to maintain plants with a minimum of technology, and some have reported success in producing lush plant growth this way.<ref>Lass, David A. (March 2009), Three tough planted tanks, ''[[Aquarium Fish International]]'', pp. 30&ndash;37.</ref> This approach, sometimes called the "natural planted tank" and popularized by [[Diana Walstad]], can include the use of soil in place of aquarium gravel, the elimination of CO<sub>2</sub> apparatus and most filtration, and limited lighting. Instead, only a few fish are kept, to limit the quantity of fish waste, and the plants themselves are used to perform the water-cleansing role typically played by aquarium filters, by utilizing what fish waste there is as fertilizer.<ref>Walstad, Diana (2003), ''Ecology of the planted aquarium: a practical manual and scientific treatise for the home aquarist'', 2nd edition, Ashland Ohio: Atlas Books, {{ISBN|0-9673773-1-5}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aquaticplantcentral.com/forumapc/el-natural |title=Online forum on the "Natural" method |publisher=Aquaticplantcentral.com |accessdate= 18 May 2012}}</ref>
== Contests ==
Early Dutch hobbyists began the practice of aquascape contests, with over 100 local clubs.<ref name=Dutch/> Judges had to go through about three years of training and pass examinations in multiple disciplines in order to qualify.<ref name=Dutch/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbkm.nl |title='&#39;Bondskeurmeesters'&#39;: Judges' website |publisher=Cbkm.nl |accessdate= 18 May 2012}}</ref> This competition continues to be held every year, under the auspices of the National Aquarium Society.<ref name=Contest/> There are three rounds, beginning with contests in local clubs. First-place local winners are entered in the second round, held in fifteen ''districtkeuring'' (districts). The winners at that level are then entered in the third round, which is the national championship.<ref name=Contest>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbat.nl |title=NBAT Dutch contest website |publisher=Nbat.nl |accessdate= 18 May 2012}}</ref>
In the Dutch contest, the focus is not only on composition, but also on the biological well-being of the aquarium's inhabitants. Most points are, in fact, awarded for such biological criteria as fish health, plant health, and water quality. Unlike contests in other countries, the judges travel to each contestant's home to evaluate the tank, where they measure the water parameters themselves.<ref name=Contest/>
The Aquatic Gardeners Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aquatic-gardeners.org/ |title=Aquatic Gardeners Association |publisher=Aquatic-gardeners.org |accessdate= 18 May 2012}}</ref> based in the United States, Aqua Design Amano,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adana.co.jp/index_e.php |title=Aqua Design Amano |publisher=Adana.co.jp |date=2012-04-27 |accessdate= 18 May 2012}}</ref> based in Japan, and AquaticScapers Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aquaticscapers.com/ |title=AquaticScapers Europe |publisher=Aquaticscapers.com |accessdate= 18 May 2012}}</ref> based in Germany, also conduct annual freshwater aquascaping contests. Entries from around the world are submitted as photographs and explanatory text online.<ref name=AGA>{{cite web|url=http://showcase.aquatic-gardeners.org/2009.cgi?&op=showpage&name=guidelines-judging |title=Aquatic Gardeners Association judging website |publisher=Showcase.aquatic-gardeners.org |accessdate= 18 May 2012}}</ref>
The Aquatic Gardeners Association contest is judged based on: :*overall impression (35&nbsp;points), :*composition, balance, use of space and use of color (30&nbsp;points), :*selection and use of materials (20&nbsp;points), and :*viability of aquascape (15&nbsp;points).<ref name=AGA/>
There are also smaller contests conducted by Acuavida in Spain,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acuavida.com/noticias/noticias-de-acuavida/244-aac-acuavida-aquascaping-contest |title=Acuavida |publisher=Acuavida. |accessdate=18 May 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611085057/http://acuavida.com/noticias/noticias-de-acuavida/244-aac-acuavida-aquascaping-contest |archivedate=11 June 2012 }}</ref> by the Greek Aquarist's Board,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aquatek.gr/ |title=Greek Aquarist's Board |publisher=Aquatek.gr |accessdate= 9 July 2017}}</ref> and by the French association Aquagora.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aquagora.fr/-Concours-AquAgora-de-Paysages- |title=Aquagora CAPA |publisher=Aquagora.fr |accessdate= 18 May 2012}}</ref>
== Public aquariums == [[File:Symphysodon.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|alt=Underwater scene, with white sand at bottom and a large piece of driftwood at the right. Various green plants grow in the sand, including a large plant with wavy leaves at the left. A shoal of blue and red striped fish swims around.|[[Discus (fish)|Discus]] and [[cardinal tetra]]s in an [[Amazon River]] [[Amazon Basin|basin]] display at the [[Palais de la Porte Dorée]] aquarium in Paris]] Large [[public aquarium]]s sometimes use aquascaping as part of their displays. As early as the 1920s, the [[New York Aquarium]] included a [[moray eel]] display tank that was decorated with [[calcareous]] [[tufa]] rock, arranged to resemble a coral reef, and supporting some [[Scleractinia|stony corals]] and [[Gorgonian|sea fans]].<ref>[[Charles Haskins Townsend|Townsend, Charles Haskins]] (1922, reprinted 2004), ''The Public Aquarium: Its Construction, Equipment, and Management'', Honolulu: University Press of the Pacific, p. 17, {{ISBN|1-4102-1147-9}}.</ref> Because they typically present wildlife from a particular habitat, modern day displays are often created to be biologically accurate biotopes.<ref>Buckley, Kate (2010), Planted aquaria for zoological parks, ''The Aquatic Gardener'', vol. 23, number 4, pp. 5–20.</ref>
