'''Bukunzi''', also known as '''Mbirizi''',<ref>[http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ahr/105.3/ah000832.html#REF29 Footnote 29] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118143857/http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ahr/105.3/ah000832.html#REF29 |date=November 18, 2009 }} of {{cite journal|last1=Newbury |first1=David |last2=Newbury |first2=Catherine |year=June 2000 |title=Bringing the Peasants Back In: Agrarian Themes in the Construction and Corrosion of Statist Historiography in Rwanda |journal=The American Historical Review |volume=105 |issue=3 |pages= |doi=10.1086/ahr/105.3.832|url=http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/ahr/105.3/ah000832.html |jstor=2651812 }}</ref> was a small kingdom located in the extreme southwest of what is now [[Rwanda]]. The kings of Bukunzi were renowned throughout the region for the legendary control of the [[rain]].<ref>Newbury 106</ref>  Located east of the [[Ruzizi River]], Bukunzi was apparently founded by members of the [[Shi people|Shi]] royal family, who fled into political exile following a family dispute. [[Luhwinja]], another small polity, is thought to have emerged from Bukunzi.<ref>Newbury 150</ref>  Located southeast of [[Lake Kivu]], its historical ties were to the west with [[Bushi (region)|Bushi]].<ref name=Newbury325>Newbury 325</ref> Through the eighteenth and nineteenth century, it had close ties to [[Ngweshe]], one of the most powerful of the Shi states.<ref>Newbury 327</ref> Bukunzi remained apart from the [[Kingdom of Rwanda|central Rwandan court]] until the military campaign led by colonial [[Belgium]] merged it into the central court in 1925, along with other small kingdoms located west of the Rwandan kingdom, such as [[Kingogo]], [[Bushiru]], and [[Busozo]].<ref>Newbury 239 & 270</ref> The area of the former Bukunzi kingdom is now part of [[Rusizi District]] in Rwanda.<ref name=Newbury325/>

