{{Mediterranean wind rose}} The '''Gregale''' ({{lang-ca|Gregal}}, {{lang-it|Grecale}}, {{Lang-lmo|Grecal}}, {{lang-mt|Grigal}}, {{Lang-oc|Gregau}}, {{lang-el|Γραίγος}}, ''Graigos'') is a [[Mediterranean]] [[wind]] that can occur during times when a [[low-pressure area]] moves through the area to the south of [[Malta]] and causes a strong, cool, northeasterly wind to affect the island. It also affects other islands of the Western [[Mediterranean]].
The name derives from the Italian ''grecale'', which refers to the island of [[Zakynthos]], in [[Greece]].{{Fact|date=September 2008}}
This is likely to be the [[Euroclydon]] wind, from Greek ''Euros'' (east) and ''kludon'' (billow, surge) or Latin ''Aquilo'' (north) "northeaster" or the island [[Gavdos|Clauda]] (Acts 27:16), which wrecked<ref>[http://www.parsagard.com/shipwreck.htm The Apostle Paul's Shipwreck: An Historical Examination of Acts 27 and 28] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217101909/http://www.parsagard.com/shipwreck.htm |date=2015-02-17 }}</ref> the [[Paul of Tarsus|apostle Paul's]] ship on the coast of [[Malta]] on his way to Rome <ref>"But not long after there arose against it a tempestuous wind, called Euroclydon."{{bibleverse||Acts|27:14|KJV}}</ref>.
==See also== *[[Bora (wind)]] *[[Etesian]] *[[Khamaseen]] *[[Levantades]] *[[Leveche]] *[[Marin (wind)]] *[[Mistral (wind)]] *[[Sirocco]]
